The '''Manufacturing clause''' is a [[clause]]{{where|date=June 2017}} specifically stating that all [[Copying|copies]] of a work must be [[printed]] or otherwise produced domestically, even if the [[copyright]] was held by a foreigner.  This was a feature of the [[International Copyright Act of 1891]], covering [[books]], [[map]]s, [[photographs]], and [[lithographs]].  Its extension to all other media was proposed in the 1897 [[Treloar Copyright Bill]], which failed in committee.  The manufacturing clause did not expire until 1986, keeping the [[United States]] out of the [[Berne Convention for the Protection of Literary and Artistic Works|Berne Convention]] until 1989.

