{{Other uses|Medea (disambiguation)}} {{Infobox Artwork | image_file=Medea-Sandys.jpg | backcolor=#FBF5DF | painting_alignment=right | image_size=250px | title= Medea | artist= [[Anthony Frederick Augustus Sandys|Frederick Sandys]] | year= 1868 | medium=[[Oil painting|Oil on canvas]] | height_metric=61.2 | width_metric=45.6 | height_imperial= | width_imperial= | metric_unit=cm | imperial_unit=in | city= [[Birmingham]] | museum= [[Birmingham Museum & Art Gallery]] }}
'''''Medea''''' is an [[oil painting]] on [[canvas]] by the [[Pre-Raphaelite]] painter [[Anthony Frederick Augustus Sandys|Frederick Sandys]] which was created in 1868. The painting was submitted to the [[Royal Academy of Arts]] for display in the Summer Exhibition of 1868 but it was rejected – most likely for internal politics and jealousies rather than artistic reasons.<ref>{{cite web |title=Medea by Anthony Frederick Sandys |publisher=Victorian Art in Britain |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080626095346/http://www.victorianartinbritain.co.uk/sandys_medea.htm |archivedate=2008-06-26 |url=http://www.victorianartinbritain.co.uk/sandys_medea.htm |accessdate=2011-06-15}}</ref> The picture was accepted the following year and reviewed very favourably by ''The Times'', which commented pointedly on its previous failure to win a place.<ref>{{cite journal|title=The Times|date=1 May 1869|page=12 "...If such a picture could be classed among the "doubtfuls" who can hereafter treat that fate as a verdict of inferiority?"}}</ref>
''Medea'' was modelled on Keomi Gray, a [[Romani people|Romani]] woman whom Sandys had met in [[Norwich]], England, and taken back to London to sit for many of his paintings.<ref>[http://www.sandys.norfolk.gov.uk/fsbiog3.htm Sandys' Love Life] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724014806/http://www.sandys.norfolk.gov.uk/fsbiog3.htm |date=2011-07-24 }} in ''Frederick Sandys & the Pre-Raphaelites'' at the Norfolk Museums and Archaeology service.</ref> According to a contemporary critic it shows the enchantress [[Medea]] "...in the act of incantation, the baleful light of her chafing-dish playing in the folds of her robe, and making the pale cheeks look paler, and the ashy lips more ashy, and kindling the array of foul ingredients and witch's properties that surround her tripod - foul toads and strange roots, and images of strange gods, and quaint shells filled with evil compounds."<ref>{{cite journal|title=The Times|date=1 May 1869|page=12 }}</ref>
In 1911 the picture was among paintings representative of the best British art sent to Italy for the [[International Exhibition of Art (1911)|international exhibition]] at Rome held in honour of the jubilee of the Kingdom of Italy.<ref>{{cite journal|journal=The Times|date=20 March 1911|page=7|title=British Art for the Rome Exhibition}}</ref>
